  {
    "poster": {
      "poster_name": "dennis edson",
      "poster_handle": "dennis261"
    },
    "time_stamp": "2020-01-20 09:41:20",
    "text": "and if so, will this work\n```/*&lt;![CDATA[*/\n            /* everything in this style tag will be inlined onto matching elements */\n            .sample-rule {\n            }\n            /*]]&gt;*/```\n"
  },
  {
    "poster": {
      "poster_name": "Jon McLaren",
      "poster_handle": "jon558"
    },
    "time_stamp": "2020-01-20 09:41:20",
    "edited": {
      "time_stamp": "2020-01-20 09:42:37"
    },
    "text": "I think it should theoretically work. most if not all email clients do support `&lt;style&gt;` in the body. Like everything in email land I suggest using the email previews to ensure it renders as you expect.\n\nThe inlining part I’m not confident on. The important bit of the inlining is the data attribute or class name. You can try implementing that though you may actually be okay without inlining anyways."
  },
  {
    "poster": {
      "poster_name": "Jon McLaren",
      "poster_handle": "jon558"
    },
    "time_stamp": "2020-01-20 09:42:59",
    "text": "<https://litmus.com/blog/do-email-marketers-and-designers-still-need-to-inline-css>"
